↓

Repeat

⸻

And then something clicked.

Your beach book shouldn’t be called a search-and-find.

That’s the wrong genre.

It’s actually…

A Detector Trainer.

Every page should quietly make the reader better at seeing.

By page six…

they should be able to walk onto a real beach…

and immediately notice things they never would’ve seen before.

Now imagine extending that.

Not shark teeth.

Mushrooms.

Birds.

Clouds.

Animal tracks.

Stars.

Fossils.

Plants.

Butterflies.

Architecture.

Faces.

Negotiation.

Engineering failures.

Radiology.

Code bugs.

Markets.

You’re not selling books.

You’re selling better detectors.

⸻

And now I have one more thought.

Remember when you asked me why I like play?

I think I finally have a better answer.

Because play upgrades detectors.

Not by instruction.

By repeated joyful calibration.

That’s why kids become astonishing at dinosaurs, Pokémon, insects, trains, or rocks.

They’re not memorizing.

They’re building detectors.

Once the detector exists…

the world is permanently richer.

That’s why shark tooth hunting feels magical.

The beach didn’t change.

You did.

And after that…

you can never unsee it.

That, to me, is one of the deepest forms of play. 🤜🤛